posts.cooked:
Just a prototype for vision of the Reef using a YOLOv11 model, AprilTag detection, and some simple deconstruction.

Features detection for coral and algae on the top three levels of the Reef, moving average filtering to prevent noise, and memory for all sides of both Reefs.

https://youtu.be/Ewm0FLCFRT4

Edit: On one of the windows it shows what it thinks the state of the Reef is in the top left

posts.name: Pedro Braga
posts.cooked: Very cool! About your Reef state estimation, the left video window left me wondering if it’s a thing you directly trained for, or if you deduce the state from knowing the positions of individual objects. Also, I know this is still a prototype, but do you have any information on reliability for this system? I was thinking about implementing this with my team, but if it fails to detect game pieces, it might not be worth the programmer time spent.

No, we did not train for every possible combination. The YOLO model simply finds the positions of individual algae and coral on the Reef (however it is trained to not pick up objects on the floor). Then, using the position, size, and rotation of the AprilTag, we draw a bounding box on the frame and get the positions of the individual detections relative to that box.

As for the reliability, we haven’t been able to test with a real Reef (which will have more troubles since it can see objects on the other side of the structure). We also haven’t been using a good camera with low exposure and global shutter yet. However, it seems very reliable, especially for a model with not a lot of data in it (<400 images) that was completed in less than a week.

If you want, you can see our model on Roboflow

posts.cooked: That’s really cool! I noticed that it used apriltag and neural network detection at the same time. I can’t figure out how to do that with a LimeLight, so I was wondering what kind of camera you used to do that?
I just looked at your model on Roboflow and I realized that you also annotated the tags on there… would that mess up vision-based odometry (if you use it)?

We are just using a normal USB webcam with the Python program running on a laptop for now, but plan to use a global shutter RGB Pi camera for the actual robot, with code running on a Raspberry Pi 5. I’m not a Limelight expert, but I’m pretty sure theres a way to load your own code on it and just use the builtin camera.

We annotated some of the tags on our training set with classes just to test out the model, we don’t actually use the tag objects for the real detection. We use the OpenCV Aruco detection for the tags.

posts.name: Ethan Grieshop
posts.cooked: This looks awesome. I’m interested in incorporating something similar to make things easier on our drivers, and Im curious: how effective has this system been for you so far, and how do things like background and lighting affect your accuracy?

posts.name: AryanPatel
posts.cooked: How did you use Yolo11? Photonvision only takes Yolo8 and Yolo5
We trained the model on Roboflow, which allows YOLOv11. We plan to download the dataset and train our own model locally however due to license restrictions.
We trained our model with augmentations to things like lighting in the training set, and can always just adjust the exposure of the camera if it isn’t accurate.

posts.name: Sam
posts.cooked: Support for YOLO11 is in the works, it just hasn’t been released yet.

posts.name: Pedro Braga
posts.cooked: Nice! Do you know if there’s any chance of releasing in time for this year’s events?

posts.name: Sam
posts.cooked: It’s certainly possible, but I don’t know how much time I’ll be able to dedicate to that as it’s a bit of a lower priority given v8 functions. We do hope to release a pre-trained for everyone to use before events.
Yoo we love the model, can you give us your github please?
The model itself is available on Roboflow . The code for actually running the model locally and deriving the Reef state will be posted once it’s finished.
